Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his unit. Silently getting out of bed, he put on his combat uniform, fastened his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying special attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he quietly left the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm, half the time it didn't work, because all that came out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching on foot.
"Ouep", replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time ?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello", said Craith.
"What woke you up ?", asked Cohren.
"Well, brother, we didn't expect to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secondo, the first shock troops on their feet are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He held out his hand and activated a switch. An alarm sounded inside the barracks, loud and shrill. He heard a commotion inside and some agitation."
"Damn it, Valturi," shouted Nemic. "One would think they would have learned to rise at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my mates from the training camp here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith and Ravik. "But, again, their squad and section leaders know how to rise before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company emerged en masse. All had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Except your respect, sir, why do you persist in waking us up like this ?", asked one of the members of the shock troop, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't do lazy mornings," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal belongings," he continued. As first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. At first, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being united. It was a split company and Cohren didn't know what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly for reasons that had motivated her.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked together under the light of the many lights of the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had used Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to fight them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are we being sent?"
"An advanced operational base outside of Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," answered Cohren as he lit his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he kept quiet.
"Damn. The situation is worsening on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from this place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren as he flicked his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're going with the first armored squad, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Shaw nous a eu un transport ?", demanda Nemic, un peu surpris.
"Ouep. Honnêtement, il n'est pas aussi mauvais que je le pensais. Je veux dire, il n'est pas exceptionnel, mais il n'est pas insupportable."
Cohren porta son pouce et son index à son micro de gorge tout en ajustant son sac à dos. "À toutes les unités de la compagnie Exodus, rendez-vous au parc de véhicules ouest lorsque vous aurez fini. Nous partons avec le premier peloton blindé à 5h00."
Toutes les quelques secondes, il recevait des réponses des chefs d'escadrons. Haris, Craith et Ravik étaient tous des sous-officiers de bas rang quand ils étaient arrivés ici. Tous les quatre étaient très bons amis depuis leur formation initiale sur Terre. Cela semblait remonter à si loin, même si cela ne pouvait pas faire plus de deux ans. Ils étaient alors chefs d'escadron. Mais Craith commandait désormais le deuxième peloton depuis une semaine, après la démobilisation du commandant précédent, blessé par un tireur d'élite de Daybreak.
Alors qu'ils marchaient vers le parc de véhicules, Cohren et Nemic virent un groupe d'environ huit chars de combat principaux Kronos et quatre Strykers. Leur équipage s'affairait, s'assurant que leurs machines de guerre étaient prêtes pour le départ. Cohren repéra rapidement le capitaine Boradin Shaw, qui parlait avec le commandant du peloton blindé. Alors qu'ils approchaient, Shaw se tourna et marcha vers eux, son visage habituellement froid ne reflétant aucune émotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol case before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
